SIMPLE: need
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Need
<hw>Need</hw> <pr>(n⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>need</ets>, <ets>neod</ets>, <ets>nede</ets>, AS.
<ets>ne⟦aacute⟧d</ets>, <ets>n⟦ymac⟧d</ets>; akin to D. <ets>nood</ets>,
G. <ets>not</ets>, <ets>noth</ets>, Icel. <ets>nau⟦edh⟧r</ets>, Sw. &
Dan. <ets>n⟦oum⟧d</ets>, Goth. <ets>nau⟦thorn⟧s</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A state that requires supply or relief; pressing
occasion for something; necessity; urgent want.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the city had no <qex>need</qex> of the sun.</q> <rj><qau>Rev.
xxi. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have no <qex>need</qex> to beg.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be governed by your <qex>needs</qex>, not by your fancy.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Want of the means of subsistence; poverty;
indigence; destitution.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Famine is in thy cheeks;⟦br⟧
<qex>Need</qex> and oppression starveth in thine eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is needful; anything necessary to be
done; (<pluf>pl.</pluf>) necessary things; business.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Situation of need; peril; danger.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Exigency; emergency; strait; extremity;
necessity; distress; destitution; poverty; indigence; want;
penury.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Need</er>, <er>Necessity</er>.
<xex>Necessity</xex> is stronger than <xex>need</xex>; it places us
under positive compulsion. We are frequently under the
<xex>necessity</xex> of going without that of which we stand very
greatly in <xex>need</xex>. It is also with the corresponding
adjectives; <xex>necessitous</xex> circumstances imply the direct
pressure of suffering; <xex>needy</xex> circumstances, the want of aid
or relief.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Need</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Need
<hw>Need</hw> <pr>(n⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Needed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Needing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Need</er>, <pos>n.</pos>
Cf. AS. <ets>n⟦ymac⟧dan</ets> to force, Goth.
<ets>nau⟦thorn⟧jan</ets>.]</ety> <def>To be in want of; to have cause or
occasion for; to lack; to require, as supply or relief.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Other creatures all day long⟦br⟧
Rove idle, unemployed, and less <qex>need</qex> rest.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ With another verb, <xex>need</xex> is used like an
auxiliary, generally in a negative sentence expressing requirement or
obligation, and in this use it undergoes no change of termination in the
third person singular of the present tense. ⟦ldquo⟧And the lender
<xex>need</xex> not fear he shall be injured.⟦rdquo⟧</note>
<rj><au>Anacharsis (Trans. ).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Need</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Need
<hw>Need</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be wanted; to be
necessary.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When we have done it, we have done all that is in our power, and
all that <qex>needs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Need</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Need
<hw>Need</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Of necessity. See
<er>Needs</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>needed</ent>⟦br⟧
